International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 6 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties(OIE), Emergency Alert Messages
[edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec7>

Vesicular stomatitis in the USA: follow-up report No. 2
-------------------------------------------------------
This information was received on (and refers up to) 1 Jul 2004 from Dr
Peter Fernandez, associate administrator, Animal and Plant Health
Inspection Service, United States Department of Agriculture (USDA),
Washington, DC:
Previous report period ended 23 Jun 2004 (see Disease Information 2004;
17[26]: 169, 25 Jun).
New outbreak:
Location and No. of outbreaks: State of Texas, Starr County 1 farm
Description of affected population in the new outbreak: the affected
premises consists of a small farm facility with 3 cows and 3 calves. There
are no other susceptible species on the premises. Only one of the 6 animals
has developed lesions compatible with vesicular stomatitis. The affected
cow has vesicular lesions located on the tip and edge of its tongue and on
its muzzle. The other cattle on the affected premises are clinically
asymptomatic.
Total number of animals in the new outbreak:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
bov / 6* / 1 / ... /... /...
* 3 cows and 3 calves
The diagnosis, of vesicular stomatitis virus type New Jersey, was made at
the National Veterinary Services Laboratories, Plum Island, New York, using
complement fixation test, competitive ELISA (enzyme-linked immunosorbent
assay), and virus isolation.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
B. Mode of spread: unknown.
Control measures:
- control of arthropods;
- quarantine of the affected premises;
- movement control inside the country;
- surveillance.
